President Muhammadu Buhari has sent a letter that was personally signed by him to the family of the late publisher and businessman, Isma’ila Isa Funtua, describing his demise as a major national loss. In the letter he wrote in Hausa, the President in a statement by his spokesman, Garba Shehu, told the bereaved wife, Hajiya Hauwa, the children and entire family members that the loss was not theirs alone, but that of the entire country. President Buhari said that, “Malam Funtua was of great assistance to me and my administration. He helped in many ways to strengthen the government and the country before his ultimely demise.” The President recalled that, ““n his active politics, Malam Isma’ila served as a minister,” adding that “he was also a businessman and contractor who built several government buildings in Abuja”. President Buhari said, “He was a director at Funtua Textile Mills for 30 years and chaired the Zamfara Textile Company”. “Malam Isma’ila was a life executive member of the Board of the International Press Institute, IPI,” he wrote. According to the President, “Nigerians of all shades and backgrounds have nothing but kind words for him,” noting that “late Funtua was reputed throughout his life for his kindness, generosity and support for public causes”. He then urged all those Malam Funtua left behind not to allow division in their ranks.
President Buhari also prayed to Allah to forgive the departed and grant him Aljannatul-Firdaus (paradise).